
Creating and Deploying the ec2 instance using Puppet module

First step
a)write a module for ec2 instance configuring security group

ec2_instance { 'my-web-server':
  ensure                => 'running',
  region                => 'us-east-1',
  availability_zone     => 'us-east-1b',
  image_id              => 'ami-696e652c',
  instance_type         => 't2.micro',
  security_groups       => ['my-web-group'],
}

This can be done manually from the AWS console 
•	Go to Ec2 instance services
•	Launch Instance
•	Choose the AMI image you want as i choose RHEL 7.3
•	Select the type of the instance you want _t1.micro/t2.micro
•	configure the instance details network,subnet.public ip/private ip (none or we can specify based on our regions)
•	specify the storage options and add storage (default)
•	configure the security group(i.e. my-web-group) 
•	Then reviewing the instance and launch the instance with the downloaded key pair or without if you have an existing  key pair.
•	Check the instance status in console and Make sure it was running
•	then,By connecting to that instance make sure that it was up to date
•	Connect to the EC2 user.
	$ chmod 400 mykeypair.pem
	$ ssh ec2-user@ip-addr -i mykeypair.pem

•	install the apache webserver
	 [ec2-user ~]$ sudo yum update -y
         [ec2-user ~]$ sudo yum install -y httpd
         [ec2-user ~]$ sudo systemctl enable httpd
         [ec2-user ~]$ sudo systemctl start httpd
	
•	cd to /var/www/html
•	vi helloworld.html
<html>
<head>
<title>Hello World</title>
</head>
<body>
<h1>Hello World!</h1>
</body>
</html>
wq!---Save and exit

If you want to deploy it through puppet here is the module written 
Module need to be written in site.pp 

node 'my-web-server'
exec { 'yum-update':                    
 command => '/usr/bin/apt-get update' 
 httpd::my-web-server { 'default-ssl':
  port                => open/443/80,
  ssl                 => true,
  docroot             => $docroot,
  docroot             => '/var/www/html/',
  scriptalias         => $scriptalias,
  security_groups     => ['Access'],
  serveradmin         => $serveradmin,
  access_log_file     => "ssl_${access_log_file}",
  }
}


“Expose   => port numbers you want to”

When you go to the ec2 instance in CLI and run
# puppet apply command


